"Dong Z.-J., Huang H., Huang L.-M., Li Y.-C.","Diversity of symbiotic algae of the genus Symbiodinium in scleractinian corals of the Xisha Islands in the South China Sea",2009,"Journal of Systematics and Evolution","47","4",,"321","326",,,10.1111/j.1759-6831.2009.00034.x,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-70349991936&partnerID=40&md5=b57cadd51e6dddbc493293a59b952dd2","Key Laboratory of Marine Bio-resourses Sustainable Utilization, South China Sea Institute of Oceanology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Guangzhou 510301, China; Yantai Institute of Coastal Zone Research for Sustainable Development, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Yantai 264003, China; Hainan Marine Development and Design Institute, Haikou 570125, China","Dong, Z.-J., Key Laboratory of Marine Bio-resourses Sustainable Utilization, South China Sea Institute of Oceanology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Guangzhou 510301, China, Yantai Institute of Coastal Zone Research for Sustainable Development, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Yantai 264003, China; Huang, H., Key Laboratory of Marine Bio-resourses Sustainable Utilization, South China Sea Institute of Oceanology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Guangzhou 510301, China; Huang, L.-M., Key Laboratory of Marine Bio-resourses Sustainable Utilization, South China Sea Institute of Oceanology, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Guangzhou 510301, China; Li, Y.-C., Hainan Marine Development and Design Institute, Haikou 570125, China","Symbiotic algae (Symbiodinium sp.) in scleractinian corals are important in understanding how coral reefs will respond to global climate change. The present paper reports on the diversity of Symbiodinium sp. in 48 scleractinian coral species from 25 genera and 10 families sampled from the Xisha Islands in the South China Sea, which were identified with the use of restriction fragment length polymorphism (RFLP) of the nuclear ribosomal DNA large subunit gene (rDNA). The results showed that: (i) Symbiodinium Clade C was the dominant zooxanthellae in scleractinian corals in the Xisha Islands; (ii) Symbiodinium Clade D was found in the corals Montipora aequituberculata, Galaxea fascicularis, and Plerogyra sinuosa; and (iii) both Symbiodinium Clades C and D were found simultaneously in Montipora digitata, Psammocora contigua, and Galaxea fascicularis. A poor capacity for symbiosis polymorphism, as uncovered by RFLP, in the Xisha Islands indicates that the scleractinian corals have low adaptability to environmental changes. Further studies are needed to investigate zooxanthellae diversity using other molecular markers. © 2009 Institute of Botany, Chinese Academy of Sciences.","Global changes; Restriction fragment length polymorphism (RFLP); Scleractinian coral; South China Sea; Symbiotic algae (Symbiodinium sp.); Xisha Islands","algae; Anthozoa; Galaxea fascicularis; Montipora aequituberculata; Montipora digitata; Plerogyra sinuosa; Psammocora contigua; Scleractinia; Symbiodinium; Symbiodinium sp.",,,,,,"Baker, A.C., Reef corals bleach to survive change (2001) Nature, 411, pp. 765-766; Baker, A.C., Flexibility and specificity in coral-algal symbiosis: Diversity, ecology, and biogeography of Symbiodinium (2003) Annual Review of Ecology Evolution and Systematics, 34, pp. 661-689; Baker, A.C., Romanski, A.M., Multiple symbiotic partnerships are common in scleractinian corals, but not in octocorals: Comment on Goulet (2006) (2007) Marine Ecology Progress Series, 335, pp. 237-242; Berkelmans, R., van Oppen, M.J.H., The role of zooxanthellae in the thermal tolerance of corals: A 'nugget of hope' for coral reefs in an era of climate change (2006) Proceedings of the Royal Society B, Biological Sciences, 273, pp. 2305-2312; Buddemeier, R.W., Fautin, D.G., Coral bleaching as an adaptive mechanism-a testable hypothesis (1993) Bio Science, 43, pp. 320-326; Carlos, A.A., Baillie, B.K., Kawachi, M., Maruyama, T., Phylogenetic position of Symbiodinium (Dinophyceae) isolates from tridacnids (Bivalvia), cardiids (Bivalvia), a sponge (Porifera), a soft coral (Anthozoa), and a free-living strain (1999) Journal of Phycology, 35, pp. 1054-1062; Chen, C.A., Katherine, K.L., Yoshikatsu, N., Tsai, W.S., A stable association of the stress-tolerant zooxanthellae, Symbiodinium Clade D, with the low-temperature-tolerant coral, Oulastrea crispata (Scleractinia: Faviidae) in subtropical non-reefal coral communities (2003) Zoological Studies, 42, pp. 540-550; Chen, C.A., Yang, Y.W., Wei, N.V., Tsai, W.S., Fang, L.S., Symbiont diversity in scleractinian corals from tropical reefs and subtropical non-reef communities in Taiwan (2005) Coral Reefs, 24, pp. 11-22; Coffroth, M.A., Santos, S.R., Genetic diversity of symbiotic dinoflagellates in the genus Symbiodinium (2005) Protist, 156, pp. 19-34; Darius, H.T., Dauga, C., Grimont, P.A.D., Chungue, E., Martin, P.M.V., Diversity in symbiotic dinoflagellates (Pyrrhophyta) from seven scleractinian corals: Restriction enzyme analysis of small subunit ribosomal RNA genes (2000) Journal of Eurkaryotic Microbiology, 45, pp. 619-627; Dong, Z.J., Huang, H., Huang, L.M., Li, Y.C., Li, X.B., PCR-RFLP analysis of large subunit rDNA of symbiotic dinoflagellates in scleractinian corals from Luhuitou fringing reef of Sanya (2008) Hainan. Biodiversity Science, 16, pp. 498-502. , in Chinese; Dong, Z.J., Huang, H., Huang, L.M., Li, Y.C., Zhou, G.W., Molecular taxonomy and diversity of symbiotic dinoflagellates in scleractinian corals near the sea off the Dongshan Island in Fujian Province (2008) Journal of Oceanography in Taiwan Strait, 27, pp. 135-140. , in Chinese; Goulet, T.L., Most corals may not change their symbionts (2006) Marine Ecology Progress Series, 321, pp. 1-7; Hoegh-Guldberg, O., Climate change, coral bleaching and the future of the world's coral reefs (1999) Marine and Freshwater Research, 50, pp. 839-866; Huang, H., Dong, Z.J., Huang, L.M., Zhang, J.B., Restriction fragment length polymorphism analysis of large subunit rDNA of symbiotic dinoflagellate